definitions.definition: To fill by packing or crowding something into; to cram with something; to load to excess.
examples: I'm going to stuff this pillow with feathers.

definitions.definition: To fill a space with (something) in a compressed manner.
examples: He stuffed his clothes into the closet and shut the door.
She stuffed the turkey for Thanksgiving using her secret recipe.

definitions.definition: To load goods into (a container ) for transport.

examples: I’m stuffed after having eaten all that turkey, mashed potatoes and delicious stuffing.

definitions.definition: To eat , especially in a hearty or greedy manner.
examples: She sits on the sofa all day, watching TV and stuffing herself with cream buns.
He skidded off the road and totally stuffed his brand new car.
His wife came home early and found him on the couch stuffing the maid.
definitions.label_groups: transitive , vulgar , British , Australia , New Zealand

definitions.definition: Used to contemptuously dismiss or reject something. See also stuff it .
examples: Stuff your stupid rules, I'll do what I like.

definitions.definition: To heavily defeat or get the better of.
examples: Mudchester Rovers were stuffed 7–0 in the semi-final.
They totally stuffed us in that business deal.

definitions.definition: To cut off another competitor in a race by disturbing his projected and committed racing line (trajectory) by an abrupt manoeuvre.
examples: I got stuffed by that guy on the supermoto going into that turn, almost causing us to crash.

definitions.definition: To preserve a dead bird or other animal by filling its skin.
To obstruct, as any of the organs; to affect with some obstruction in the organs of sense or respiration.
To form or fashion by packing with the necessary material.
To crowd with facts; to cram the mind of; sometimes, to crowd or fill with false or idle tales or fancies.
To compress (a file or files) in the StuffIt format, to be unstuffed later.
